<div class="container-fluid">
  <h1 class="text-center primary-text" style="margin: 10px 0 25px 0">Mahatama Gandhi</h1>
  <h2 class="text-center" style="color:grey; font-size:25px"><i>Father Of The Nation</i></h2>
  <figure><img src ="https://thinkloud65.files.wordpress.com/2012/03/dandi-march.jpg" class="figure-img img-responsive" alt="Gandhi picked salt during Salt Satyagraha to defy colonial law giving salt collection monopoly to the British. His satyagraha attracted vast numbers of Indian men and women">
    <figcaption class="figure-caption">Gandhi picking salt during Salt Satyagraha to defy colonial law giving salt collection monopoly to the British.</figcaption>
  </figure>
  <p style="margin: 10px 0 10px 0"><b>Here is the timeline of Mahatama Gandhi:</b></p>
  <ul style="font-family:calibri">
    <li>1869
Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi is Born in Gujarat, India</li>
    <li>1876
Mohandas Gandhi Begins Primary School in Rajkot</li>
    <li>1881
Mohandas Gandhi Enters High School in Rajkot</li>
    <li>1883
Mohandas Gandhi Marries Kasturbai Makhanji in an Arranged Child Marriage</li>
    <li>1884
Mohandas Gandhi Enters Rebellious Adolescent Phase, Engaging in Activities He Will Soon Reject</li>
    <li>1885
Mohandas Gandhi's Father Dies at 63</li>
    <li>1888
Mohandes Gandhi Travels to London to Train as a Barrister</li>
    <li>1891
Mohandes Gandhi Returns to India from London After Passing the Bar</li>
    <li>1893
Mohandes Gandhi Travels to South Africa to Work Under a Year-Long Contract with Dada Abdulla & Co., an Indian Firm</li>
    <li>1893
Mahatma Gandhi is Ejected from a South African Train, Motivating Him to Fight for Indian Rights in the British Colony</li>
    <li>1894
Mohandes Gandhi Founds the Natal Indian Congress</li>
    <li>1897
Mohandes Gandhi is Nearly Lynched by White Settlers in Durban upon Returning from a Brief Trip to Fetch his Family in India</li>
    <li>1899
Gandhi Organizes an Indian Ambulance Corps of 1100 Men During His Service in the Boer War</li>
    <li>1904
Gandhi Founds the Phoenix Settlement</li>
    <li>1906
Asiatic Law Amendment Ordinance Requires Asians in Transvaal to Carry Fingerprinted Identification</li>
    <li>1906
Gandhi Introduces Non-Violent Protest Philosophy of Satyagraha</li>
    <li>1908
Gandhi is Arrested for the First Time, for Refusing to Carry an Obligatory ID Card in South Africa</li>
    <li>1910
Gandhi Establishes the Tolstoy Farm, which Serves as a Base of Operations for His Activities in South Africa</li>
    <li>1913
Gandhi Begins "Great March" to Gain Indian Rights in South Africa</li>
    <li>1914
Gandhi Suspends South African Struggle After Winning Passage of the Indian Relief Act</li>
    <li>1915
Gandhi Receives Hero's Welcome Upon Returning to India from South Africa</li>
    <li>1917
Gandhi Establishes Sabarmati Ashram</li>
    <li>1918
Gandhi Begins Advocating on Behalf of Farmers in Kheda Subject to Oppressive Taxation During a Famine</li>
    <li>1919
British Government Passes the Rowlatt Act in Colonial India, Indefinitely Extending the Use of 'Emergency Measures'</li>
    <li>1920
The Gandhi Era of the Indian Independence Movement Begins with the Non-Cooperation Movement</li>
    <li>1921
Gandhi is Given Exclusive Authority Over the Indian National Congress</li>
    <li>1922
Gandhi is Arrested by the British Government on Charges of Inciting Violence at Chauri Chaura</li>
    <li>1924
Gandhi is Released from Prison After Serving Only Two Years of a Six-Year Sentence Following Surgery for Appendicitis</li>
    <li>1924
Gandhi Begins Twenty-One Day Fast in an Attempt to Reconcile Hindus and Muslims</li>
    <li>1927
Gandhi's 'The Story of My Experiments with Truth' is Published</li>
    <li>1929
Indian National Congress Raises the Tricolor Flag of India</li>
    <li>1930
Mahatma Gandhi Embarks on the Salt Satyagraha</li>
    <li>1931
Lord Irwin, Viceroy of India, Signs the Gandhi-Irwin Pact</li>
    <li>1931
Gandhi Sets Sail for England to Represent the Indian National Congress at the Second Round Table Conference</li>
    <li>1932
Gandhi Begins Six-Day Fast to Protest Separate Elections for Untouchables</li>
    <li>1936
Gandhi Relocates Base of Operations to Sevagram, a Small Village Near Wardha in Central India</li>
    <li>1942
The Cripps' Mission</li>
    <li>1942
The All India Congress Committee Launches the Quit India Movement</li>
    <li>1944
Kasturba Gandhi Dies at Age 74</li>
    <li>1946
The British Cabinet Mission Arrives in India</li>
    <li>1946
Direct Action Day, Also Known as the "Great Calcutta Killing"</li>
    <li>1946
Formation of the Interim Government of India
</li>
    <li>1947
United Kingdom Passes the Indian Independence Act 1947</li>
    <li>1947
The Partition of India</li>
    <li>1948
Mahatma Gandhi Announces Fast to End Hindu/Muslim Violence in Delhi</li>
    <li>1948
Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi is Assassinated by Nathuram Godse</li>
  </ul>
  <p><i style = 'font-family:verdana;font-size:20px'>"I am mindful that I might not be standing before you today, as President of the United States, had it not been for Gandhi and the message he shared with America and the world."</i> - Barack Obama, US President</p>
  <p style = "margin-top:20px; font-family:calibri font-size:16px">If you have time, you should read more about this incredible human being on his <a href = 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahatma_Gandhi' target='blank'>Wikipedia Entry</a>.</p>
</div>

